Optimal binning

  • Note: important to make sure that any feature engineering you do base don the dependent variable is done solely on the training set, and then said features are applied to the testing
    • ex mean(dependent per) per bin of the independent
    • if you derive this on the testing youll be cheating and you model wont generalize
library(smbinning)
## Loading required package: sqldf
## Loading required package: gsubfn
## Loading required package: proto
## Loading required package: RSQLite
## Loading required package: partykit
## Loading required package: grid
## Loading required package: Formula
opt_bin <- function(train, test, hold, feats, dep='y', p=.1) {
  # compute optimal bins for each feature and add new cols into train and test
  # NOTE: important not to do this on the whole dataframe
  # p = proportion of 
  
  #tr <- train[,] # dont change a variable inside a function copy it
  tr <- data.frame(train[,]) # dont change a variable inside a function copy it
  #print(str_c('max of tr$y: ', max(tr$y)))
  tr$y <- tr$y*1
  #print(str_c('max of tr$y: ', max(tr$y)))
  te <- data.frame(test[,])
  h <- data.frame(hold[,])
  for (f in feats) {
    print(str_c('max of tr$y (should == 1, if not probably empty): ', max(tr$y)))
    smb <- smbinning(df=tr, y=dep, x=f, p=p)
    if (!is.character(smb)) {
      try(smbinning.plot(smb, option='WoE', sub=f))
      tr <- smbinning.gen(tr, smb, chrname=str_c(f, '_opt_bin'))
      te <- smbinning.gen(te, smb, chrname=str_c(f, '_opt_bin'))
      h <- smbinning.gen(te, smb, chrname=str_c(f, '_opt_bin'))
    }
    else {
      print(smb)
    }
  }
  
  return(list(train=tr, test=te, hold=h))
}

feats <- c('stockitemid_mean', 'stockitemid_median',
       'stockitemid_len', 'stockitemid_count_gt_n',
       'customerid_mean', 'customerid_median', 'customerid_len',
       'customerid_count_gt_n'
       )

roc_glm_df <- function(train, test, glm) {
  trprobs <- predict(glm, newdata=train, type='response')
  trperf <- performance(prediction(trprobs, train$y),
                        measure='tpr', x.measure='fpr')
  teprobs <- predict(glm, newdata=test, type='response')
  teperf <- performance(prediction(teprobs, test$y),
                        measure='tpr', x.measure='fpr')
  rocdf <- rbind(
    data.frame(fpr = unlist(trperf@x.values),
               tpr = unlist(trperf@y.values),
               model='train'),
    data.frame(fpr = unlist(teperf@x.values),
               tpr = unlist(teperf@y.values),
               model='test')
  )
  return (rocdf)
}

rocdf <- roc_glm_df(trf, tef, glm1)
